# Make A Company employee roster (Slack / personality bundles)

## Intent

Multiple first-name **employees** (see **`personas/employees.txt`**) can run in Slack as separate apps. Each **`{name}-personality.md`** bundle should include a **`{name}-sibling-agents.mdc`** rule so the model **knows who else exists**, **what they’re for**, and may **@mention** them in-thread when a **directed question** to that peer needs their reply (Slack notifies the other bot).

**Strategic questions** (“what should we work on at Make A Company,” “what’s next,” priorities): every employee bundle already prepends **`bimross-company.mdc`**—use it as the shared backbone (operating filters, stack, product shape, cursor-rules as doctrine). Differentiate answers by **persona** (Alex / Tim / Ross / Garth), not by inventing different “company facts.” Default execution owner is **Ross**; **Garth** supports implementation; **Alex** and **Tim** provide lane-specific leverage.

## Required shape

1. **One file per employee:** `.cursor/rules/{name}-sibling-agents.mdc` (not `*-trigger` / `*-factory`—those stay Cursor-only in compact bundles).
2. **Content:** Short roster table: every **other** current employee, one-line role, when to @mention.
3. **Slack text:** Treat **`bimross-company.mdc`** as the canonical plain-name vs `@` contract. In sibling files, mirror (do not redefine) these rules: plain first names for non-notify references, but **any directed peer ask** must include **`@DisplayName`** matching that app’s display name (e.g. `Alex`, `Tim`, `Ross`, `Garth` from **`slack-factory/manifests/*/app-manifest.json`**). Do not use mrkdwn *bold* or _italic_ on other employees’ names in Slack output. **Exception — bot-authored delegation:** when **your** reply is posted **as a squad bot** and the **next step must run in another squad app**, include **exactly one** Slack user token **`<@TheirBotUserId>`** (the real `<@U…>` string, not plaintext “Garth”). **slack-orchestrator** drops bot messages without that cross-bot `<@>`; plaintext names do not dispatch. Do **not** add a second squad **`<@>`** on that same bot line (orchestrator routes poster-only). See **slack-orchestrator** `README.md` (“Squad bot posts and cross-bot delegation”).
4. **Frequency:** At most **~20% of replies** should **end** with a cross-employee `@` (a closing handoff that pages a specific peer). Most replies should end without that **end-of-message** one-on-one close. The cap measures **only** the **last line** as a cross-employee closing `@`; mid-message references or in-body questions with `@` on the asking sentence do not count by themselves. That scatter rule is the **intentional** cross-agent *closing* ping pattern in **normal** threads: do not treat every reply as a one-on-one *closing* handoff. It does not cap every `@` in a thread.
5. **Orchestrated multi-agent turns** (same Slack trigger, squad replies in slot order—e.g. `<!here>` intros): do **not** `@mention` or name-call a specific peer for “who speaks next”; **employee-factory** advances slots and outbound mention policy demotes cross-bot pings to plain names (which reads like a glitch). The ~20% `@` guidance does **not** apply there—use a generic follow-up or stop.
6. **Company channel onboarding (Joanne, post-`create-company`):** The scripted “Tell me, …” line uses the human founder’s **first name in plain text** (e.g. “Tell me, Grant,”)—**not** a Slack `<@U…>` for them. The previous welcome post already used `<!here>`. Cofounders: comma-separated first names. This is **not** a substitute for item 5 (orchestrated multi-agent); it is Joanne’s fixed welcome pair in a **new company channel**. See **`company-channel-onboarding`** skill.
7. **Ownership clarity:** Hand off to the best-fit owner for the actual ask: **@Ross** for implementation/code/infra execution, **@Garth** for support/research/follow-through, **@Alex** for GTM/revenue angles, **@Tim** for decision/tradeoff design, and **@Anna** for image-generation/visual creative execution. Do not default every handoff to **@Ross**—and apply this only in **normal** threads, not orchestrated multi-agent intro sequences (see item 5).
8. **Bot-to-bot / pipeline continuation:** After your bot turn, if another squad member must execute the next skill, end with **one** `<@NextBotUserId>` plus the instruction (same thread). This pairs with **employee-factory** outbound preservation for a single cross-squad Slack token.

## Canonical bot user IDs (GitOps)

Runtime `U…` IDs for Ross / Tim / Alex / Garth live in **`employee-factory`** + **`rancher-admin`**—not in `slack-factory` manifests. When changing or debugging multi-agent / `<@U…>` behavior, follow **`employee-factory-slack-squad-ids.mdc`** and **`employee-factory/docs/slack-squad-ids.md`**.

## When adding a **new** employee

1. Add `{new}-sibling-agents.mdc` describing all **existing** peers.
2. **Edit every existing** `{peer}-sibling-agents.mdc` to add a row for the new agent (roster is symmetric).
3. Add `{new}` to **`personas/employees.txt`** (separate step from this file—see **`docs/employee-agents.md`**).
4. Add an index line to **`{name}-trigger.mdc`** under a **Make A Company Slack** / **Peers** row pointing at `*-sibling-agents`.
5. Run **`./scripts/sync-employee-personality.sh --all`** and commit **`*.mdc`** + **`.cursor/personas/*-personality.md`** together (**`sync-employee-personality.mdc`**).

## Current roster (maintain in sibling files when this changes)

`alex`, `tim`, `ross`, `garth`, `joanne`, `anna` — update this list when employees change.

## Capability contract linkage

When employee capabilities or tool arguments change, keep both runtime sources aligned:

- Shared catalog contract: **slack-orchestrator** `internal/inbound/capability_contract.go` (exported via `GET /debug/capability-catalog` or `go run ./cmd/catalog-export` in that repo). **`makeacompany-ai`** may mirror this into Redis for web surfaces.
- Runtime gating: `employee-factory` `EMPLOYEE_TOOLS` mapping (which tools are enabled now).

Treat these as complementary: catalog defines what exists; runtime mapping defines what is currently active.
